Let’s think step by step.  A sequence is arithmetic (or "straight line") if and only if each term can be obtained from adding or subtracting a constant ("the common difference") to the previous term.  To determine this difference, we look at consecutive terms of the sequence:  $a_1, a_2$  We will want: \begin{align*}
a_2&=a_1+d
\end{align*} In our case we know $a_1=3^2=9$, and $a_3=3^4=81$, so  \begin{align*}
81&=9+d\\
\Rightarrow\qquad d&=81-9=\boxed{72}
\end{align*} Our sequence then begins:  $9, 9+72, 9+2(72)$.  But we know that $9+72$, $x$, is somewhere in this sequence.  Thus, by having our terms equal: \begin{align*}
9+72=x
\end{align*} And, since we know the difference, we can let: \begin{align*}
x=9+72=\boxed{9+72=81}
\end{align*}
